"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749450","Home Office","false","2017-07-12","<p>Home Office officials met with the British Bankers’ Association to discuss a range of issues, including the process of opening a bank account for refugees.</p><p> </p><p>To help refugees to prove their identity, when an individual is granted refugee status by the Home Office they are issued with a Biometric Residence Permit (BRP) as proof of the holder’s right to stay, work or study in the UK.</p><p> </p><p>How firms verify their customers’ identities is not stipulated in law or by the regulator. Banks may ask for driving licences and passports as forms of identification, as they are the most commonly encountered documents, but banks are not required to demand sight of them, and are encouraged to act reasonably and consider a wide range of other forms of identification.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-07-12T09:26:55.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749450/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749450/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749450/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-06","Refugees: Bank Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what discussions her Department has had with the British Bankers' Association on the process of opening a bank account for refugees who have been granted asylum in the UK.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","3377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749451","Home Office","false","2017-07-11","<p>The National Transfer Scheme was launched on 1 July 2016 and has been working to ensure a fairer allocation of unaccompanied asylum seeking children (UASC) across the UK. A significant number of local authorities have participated in the scheme and enabled the transfer of children away from local authorities with a disproportionate number of UASC in their care.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-07-11T16:07:00.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749451/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749451/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749451/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-06","Asylum: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many unaccompanied children have been transferred under section 69 of the Immigration Act 2016 in the last six months.","false","Biography information for Gavin Newlands","Paisley and Renfrewshire North","Gavin Newlands","3378"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749452","Home Office","false","2017-07-12","<p>Under the Family Reunion Rules, children cannot sponsor family members. Where an application does not meet the Immigration Rules, we consider whether there are exceptional or compassionate reasons for granting a visa outside the Rules.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-07-12T09:19:28.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749452/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749452/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749452/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-06","Refugees: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what her Department's policy is on allowing unaccompanied refugee children to sponsor their parents for the purpose of family reunion.","false","Biography information for Gavin Newlands","Paisley and Renfrewshire North","Gavin Newlands","3543"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749453","House of Commons Commission","false","2017-07-18","<p>The Joint Committee on the Palace of Westminster, published its report on the Restoration and Renewal (R&amp;R) of the Palace of Westminster in September 2016.[1]</p><p>The report set out next steps for the Programme,[2] based on the Joint Committee’s recommendation that a full decant be undertaken to deliver the works, stressing that timings were indicative only and that it will be for the proposed Delivery Authority, once established, to put together a more detailed schedule for the development of the Programme.</p><p>The Independent Options Appraisal produced by the Deloitte-led consortium and published in June 2015 provided estimates of the inflationary impact on capital expenditure of a delay to the construction start date. A range of estimates were provided across the options under consideration and at different levels of certainty. Based on the scenario of full decant, as recommended by the Joint Committee, with some defined improvements to the Palace, the range of predicted inflationary impacts was £78m to £167m per annum.[3]</p><p>Additional costs for ongoing maintenance to the Palace will also continue to be incurred.</p><p /> <p>[1] HL Paper 41 / HC 639, published 8 September 2016.</p><p>[2] p90, next steps for the R&amp;R programme</p><p>[3] The Independent Options Appraisal analysis was based on an assumed start date of Q2 2020 delayed to Q2 2025</p>","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake",,"2017-07-18T09:56:56.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749453/answer","Biography information for Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749453/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749453/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2017-07-06","Palace of Westminster: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Carshalton and Wallington, representing the House of Commons Commission, what estimate it has made of the cost of a change in the timetable for a decision on the proposed restoration and renewal programme for the Palace of Westminster.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","3465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749454","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-07-11","<p>While we have not had any discussions on these specific issues with the Palestinian Authority (PA), a UK delegation led by the Foreign and Commonwealth Office Permanent Under-Secretary raised the issue of incitement with the PA on 21 June. The UK continues to urge the Palestinian leadership to avoid engaging in, or encouraging, any type of action and language that makes it more difficult to achieve a negotiated solution to the conflict.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-07-11T15:54:07.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749454/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749454/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749454/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-06","Karim and Maher Younes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with the Palestinian Authority on the naming of a square in Jenin after Karim Younes and a square in Tulkarem after Maher Younes.","true","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","3584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749455","Department for International Development","false","2017-07-11","<p>As set out in DFID’s Economic Development Strategy, which I launched earlier this year, we are helping African countries to improve their investment climates so that new industries can flourish. This includes tackling constraints on start-ups, job creation and investment which will help the creative industries along with other emerging businesses in Africa to succeed.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-07-11T16:47:27.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749455/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749455/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749455/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-07-06","Africa: Arts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to support creative industries across Africa.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","3591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749456","Department for International Development","false","2017-07-12","<p>The UN has just completed an updated assessment of the humanitarian needs in and around Mosul. The UN estimates that the cost of humanitarian assistance, which includes funding to meet basic needs such as shelter, healthcare, education and water facilities, could be up to $450 million. This has been factored into the UN’s 2017 Humanitarian Response Plan (HRP), which puts funding requirements for the whole of Iraq for 2017 at $984.6 million. The UK continues to work with the UN and lobby the international community to ensure that humanitarian partners have sufficient funding to meet the needs of vulnerable Iraqis.</p><p>The Department for International Development is monitoring the situation on a daily basis.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-07-12T15:46:32.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749456/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749456/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749456/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-07-06","Iraq: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the level for humanitarian support from the international community required for the people of Mosul following that city's recapture from Da'esh.","false","Biography information for Edward Argar","Charnwood","Edward Argar","3376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749457","Department for International Development","false","2017-07-12","<p>DFID is providing regular advice to support departments to improve the transparency of their overseas development assistance. This includes workshops, guidance and the establishment of a network to share good practice. It is essential we pool skills and expertise across government to ensure we achieve this commitment, so the British public know their money is being spent well to eradicate poverty and keep Britain safe.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-07-12T16:01:33.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749457/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749457/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749457/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-07-06","Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to help other government departments that spend aid achieve Good or Very Good ratings under the International Aid Transparency Initiative.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","3387"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749458","Department for International Development","false","2017-07-12","<p>No DFID staff have left or agreed settlements under voluntary exit or redundancy nor had any compulsory redundancy since 1 November 2016.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-07-12T15:56:57.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749458/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749458/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749458/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-07-06","Department for International Development: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many staff have left or agreed settlements to leave her Department under (a) voluntary exit, (b) voluntary redundancy and (c) compulsory redundancy since 1 November 2016; and how much compensation was paid in those cases.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","3365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749459","Department for International Development","false","2017-07-13","<p>DFID is a longstanding supporter of Fairtrade and other standards organisations which fall under the International Social and Environmental Accreditation and Labelling (ISEAL) Alliance umbrella. Certification by these organisations assures consumers that standards are being met and can help producers receive a better price for their goods. There is not yet sufficient information available on the Sainsbury’s Sustainability Standards for DFID to make an assessment. Officials will monitor the progress of the scheme, including its impact on Fairtrade.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-07-13T16:45:27.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749459/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749459/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749459/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-07-06","Fairtrade Initiative","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if she will make an assessment on the effect on the Fairtrade scheme of the decision of Sainsbury's and other retailers to withdraw from that scheme; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","3300"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749460","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-13","<p>The Secretary of State for Justice has not met Mr Justice McCloskey, but work is ongoing to reduce delays in immigration tribunals.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-07-13T15:02:30.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749460/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749460/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749460/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-06","Immigration: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when he last met Mr Justice McCloskey to discuss delays in immigration tribunals.","true","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","3322"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749461","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-11","<p>The construction of central registers or similarly effective systems is complete in all our Crown Dependencies. Legislation to underpin the registers has been passed by their respective legislatures. Guernsey and Alderney’s legislation to enable their registers to be operational will be considered by the Privy Council this month. Population of the registers with data will be taken forward as a priority in the coming months.</p><p> </p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-07-11T15:35:26.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749461/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749461/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749461/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-06","Crown Dependencies: Companies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, which of the UK's Crown Dependencies have a fully functional register of beneficial ownership; and which of those dependencies does not have such a fully-functional register.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","3349"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749462","Department of Health","false","2017-07-11","<p>Figures from NHS England state that in the financial year 2016/17 there were 711 reported transfers where the waiting time was longer than 14 days.</p><p> </p><p>It is important to note that an individual prisoner may have undergone more than one transfer during the time period.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-07-11T13:53:17.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749462/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749462/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749462/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-06","Prisoners: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many prisoners waited more than 14 days for a transfer to hospital under the Mental Health Act 1983 in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","3342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749463","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-13","<p>Information on the number of Ministry of Justice (MoJ) staff who left the Department under Voluntary Exit, Voluntary Redundancy and Compulsory Redundancy, as well as the cost of these exits between 1 November 2016 and 31 March 2017 is contained in the table below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Number of Staff who left</p></td><td><p>Cost (£)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Voluntary Exit</p></td><td><p>56</p></td><td><p>2,415,060.16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Voluntary Redundancy</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Compulsory Redundancy</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-07-13T14:59:21.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749463/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749463/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749463/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-06","Ministry of Justice: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many staff have left or agreed settlements to leave his Department under (a) voluntary exit, (b) voluntary redundancy and (c) compulsory redundancy since 1 November 2016; and how much compensation was paid in those cases.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","3367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749464","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-14","<p>The most recent published data on reoffending rates is for the period commencing July 2014 to July 2015.The information requested is available via the following link:</p><p> </p><ul><li>Link to the proven reoffending statistics quarterly main page: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/proven-reoffending-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/proven-reoffending-statistics</a></li><li>Link to proven reoffending tables, July 2014 to June 2015: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/611003/proven-reoffending-jul14-jun15.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/611003/proven-reoffending-jul14-jun15.xlsx</a></li></ul>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-07-14T10:22:16.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749464/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749464/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749464/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-06","Reoffenders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the reoffending rates for (a) short-term and (b) long-term prisoners were in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jonathan Lord","Woking","Mr Jonathan Lord","3371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749465","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-13","<p>The proportion of offenders convicted or cautioned for possession of an offensive weapon who received a non-custodial sentence in the last three years, and the proportion who were juveniles, can be viewed in the following table.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="9"><p><strong>Offenders convicted or cautioned for possession of an offensive weapon, England and Wales<sup>1</sup>, year ending March 2015 to year ending March 2017</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Year Ending March</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Proportion of those who were convicted or cautioned who received a non-custodial sentence<sup>2,3</sup></strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Proportion of those who were convicted or cautioned and received a non-custodial sentence who were juvenile<sup>2,3</sup></strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>57%</p></td><td><p>27%</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>54%</p></td><td><p>31%</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017 <sup>4</sup></p></td><td><p>51%</p></td><td><p>35%</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="3"><p><strong>Source: </strong>MoJ extract of the National Computer</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Notes:</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="4"><p>1) England and Wales includes all 43 police force areas and the British Transport Police.</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="9"><p>2) The disposal considered in this table is only the most severe of the disposals given as a result of the offender being found guilty and may also be dependent on other offences committed at the same time.</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="9"><p>3) A custodial sentence includes immediate custody and suspended sentences. Non-custodial sentences refer to other sanctions including community sentences, cautions, fines, absolute or conditional discharges and other disposals such as restraining orders.</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="9"><p>4) The proportion of those convicted who were juvenile has been estimated from raw figures to which no estimation method has been applied.</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-07-13T15:20:31.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749465/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749465/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749465/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-06","Offensive Weapons: Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what proportion of offenders charged with possession of an offensive weapon received non-custodial sentences in each of the last three years; and what proportion of those offenders were juveniles.","false","Biography information for Mr Jonathan Lord","Woking","Mr Jonathan Lord","3373"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749466","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-13","<p>The reforms to the scope of civil legal aid were designed to refocus funding on those who need it most and on the most serious cases in which legal advice and representation are justified.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Previous Ministers have made a commitment to publishing both a post-legislative memorandum for the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012 as a whole and a post-implementation review of recent legal aid reform.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-07-13T15:20:37.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749466/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749466/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749466/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-06","Legal Aid Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps the Government is taking to increase the availability of legal aid in England and Wales.","false","Biography information for Tonia Antoniazzi","Gower","Tonia Antoniazzi","3580"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749469","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-14","<p>There are currently no external organisations delivering specific educational activities on Hate Crime, racism or discrimination as part of prisoner rehabilitation work.</p><p>All new prisoners go through a local induction programme that promotes tolerance for protected characteristics. It also advises on the process for reporting incidents in prison that might be considered hate crimes through the prisoner complaint system or to prison staff.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-07-14T10:34:08.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749469/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749469/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749469/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-06","Prisoners: Rehabilitation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, which organisations have been given clearance to run educational activities on hate crime, racism or discrimination as part of prisoner rehabilitation work.","false","Biography information for Ellie Reeves","Lewisham West and Penge","Ellie Reeves","3463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749470","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-20","<p>Over the period of January 2016 – July 2017, the MOJ spent £24,912.52 on social media advertising. <br> This spend was with Facebook and was to support the recruitment of prison officers by HMPPS.</p><p> </p><p>Detail of the spend by month is shown in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Month</p></td><td><p>Spend</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-01-01</p></td><td><p>£2,640.00</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-01-02</p></td><td><p>3,397.90</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-01-03</p></td><td><p>1,322.81</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-01-04</p></td><td><p>£76.30</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-01-05</p></td><td><p>-</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-01-06</p></td><td><p>£450.00</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-01-07</p></td><td><p>£150.00</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-01-08</p></td><td><p>£543.21</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-01-09</p></td><td><p>£377.78</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-01-10</p></td><td><p>£1,620.31</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-01-11</p></td><td><p>£623.48</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-01-12</p></td><td><p>£202.50</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017-01-01</p></td><td><p>£2,088.20</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017-01-02</p></td><td><p>£1,000.03</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017-01-03</p></td><td><p>£796.75</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017-01-04</p></td><td><p>£4,359.14</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017-01-05</p></td><td><p>£2,342.30</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017-01-06</p></td><td><p>£2,921.81</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>£24,912.52</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><br> Government advertising is purchased by our media buying partner, Carat. Carat has held the contract for UK Government media buying since January 2015. These values have been confirmed by Carat.</p><p> </p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-07-20T15:36:22.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749470/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749470/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749470/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-06","Ministry of Justice: Advertising","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much his Department has spent on advertising on social media in each month since January 2016.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","3411"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749471","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-14","<p>All new prisoners go through a local induction programme that promotes tolerance for protected characteristics. It also advises on the process for reporting incidents in prison that might be considered hate crimes through the prisoner complaint system or to prison staff. The Thinking Skills Programme encourages participants to develop pro-social attitudes and manage relationships with other people. There are no specific sponsored programmes for educating prisoners on these issues.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-07-14T10:42:09.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749471/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749471/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749471/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-06","Prisons: Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what programmes his Department sponsors across the prison system to educate prisoners against (a) racism, (b) anti-Semitism, (c) Islamophobia and (d) homophobia.","false","Biography information for Ellie Reeves","Lewisham West and Penge","Ellie Reeves","3452"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749472","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-14","<p>Electronic Monitoring is an important tool to improve supervision in the community and support offenders to change their lives. The Electronic Monitoring service has always been delivered using a contracted infrastructure. Estimating the cost of a public sector delivery model could only be provided at a disproportionate cost.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-07-14T13:41:17.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749472/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749472/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749472/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-06","Electronic Tagging","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what estimate he has made of the savings to the public purse of out-sourcing electronic tagging for ex-offenders.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","3567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749473","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-14","<p>In March 2016, G4S became the sole provider of Personal Information Devices (PIDs) – commonly referred to as tags after taking over the contract to supply electronic monitoring equipment from the previous joint provider Serco. The contractual arrangements entered into with G4S and Serco in 2014 were different, the Ministry of Justice purchased equipment from G4S while the equipment was leased from Serco. The data recording requirements were therefore different and there is no comparable data of sufficient quality available for Serco equipment.</p><p> </p><p>The answer provided refers to lost and broken PIDs for all individuals subject to a curfew requirement.</p><p> </p><p>Table 1: Lost G4S Personal Identification Devices (tags) [1]</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>Financial Year 2015/16</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Net Losses</strong></p></td><td><p>5,236</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Table 2: Broken G4S Personal Identification Devices (tags) [2]</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>Financial Year 2015/16</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Sent for repairs</strong></p></td><td><p>11,626</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>PIDs are deemed to be lost if they are not recovered within four weeks of the end of the electronic monitoring order. Therefore, none of the lost tags relate to individuals who are still subject to electronic monitoring.</p><p> </p><p>[1] The data applies to Radio Frequency (RF) Personal Identification Devices (tags) only.</p><p> </p><p>[2] The data applies to Radio Frequency (RF) Personal Identification Devices (tags) only.</p><p>‘Broken’ indicates the RF tag was sent for repair. There are a variety of reasons why PIDS can be sent for repair including (but not restricted too) low battery life, damage, (including that caused by the subject), and faults. The need for a repair can be determined at any time, thus not all PIDS sent for repair will have been fitted to a subject. A fault may be established during the installation process hence there should not be assumed to be a relationship between the numbers of repairs and the actively monitored caseload. Damage is most often caused by the subjects wearing the PID, so it should not be assumed that damage is the result of a manufacturing issue.</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-07-14T13:41:12.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749473/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749473/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749473/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-06","Electronic Tagging","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many electronic tags used by the Electronic Monitoring Service to monitor ex-offenders have been reported (a) faulty and (b) lost.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","3566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749474","Leader of the House","false","2017-07-11","<p>The Government has set out an ambitious programme of 27 bills and drafts bills and noted that additional bills will be announced as the session progresses. The timescales for forthcoming bills and draft bills will be announced in the usual manner in due course<strong>. </strong></p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2017-07-11T16:09:32.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749474/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749474/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749474/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2017-07-06","Courts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, when and in which House the Government plans to introduce the Courts Bill.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","3491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749475","Leader of the House","false","2017-07-11","<p>The Government has set out an ambitious programme of 27 bills and drafts bills and noted that additional bills will be announced as the session progresses. The timescales for forthcoming bills and draft bills will be announced in the usual manner in due course.</p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2017-07-11T16:11:25.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749475/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749475/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749475/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2017-07-06","Patients: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, when and in which House the Government plans to introduce the Patient Safety Bill.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","3492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749476","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-07-13","<p>Since January 2016, the Department has not incurred any expenditure for advertising on social media.</p>","Norwich North","Chloe Smith",,"2017-07-13T14:47:59.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749476/answer","Biography information for Chloe Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749476/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749476/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-07-06","Northern Ireland Office: Advertising","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how much his Department has spent on advertising on social media in each month since January 2016.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","3412"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749477","Prime Minister","false","2017-07-14","<p>I discussed these issues with President Erdogan during the G20 Summit in Hamburg emphasising the importance of fundamental rights and rule of law. We regularly engage in a broad and comprehensive dialogue with Turkey at ministerial level.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2017-07-14T12:03:41.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749477/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749477/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749477/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-07-06","Turkey: Human Rights and Press Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, what recent discussions she has had with President Erdogan of Turkey on (a) human rights and (b) press freedom in that country.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","3473"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749478","Prime Minister","false","2017-07-14","<p>There is no requirement for domestic visits to be authorised and the information is not held centrally. I have not authorised overseas travel by any Parliamentary Private Secretary in an official capacity since I took Office.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2017-07-14T12:06:17.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749478/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749478/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749478/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-07-06","Parliamentary Private Secretaries: Travel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, how many parliamentary private secretaries have undertaken travel (a) within the UK and (b) overseas with or on behalf of ministers since she became Prime Minister.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","3466"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749479","Home Office","false","2017-07-14","<p>The Government recognises the importance of appropriate identity checking processes. It is a matter for each organisation to determine how this is done in a way that protects them and their customers.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-07-14T13:34:13.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749479/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749479/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749479/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-06","Airbnb: Passports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will discuss with Airbnb the security implications of the requirement by some hosts for guests to send the photograph page of their passport to secure a booking.","false","Biography information for Chris Bryant","Rhondda","Chris Bryant","3467"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749480","Prime Minister","false","2017-07-14","<p>While I met President Putin at this G20, my last substantive bilateral with him was at the G20 Summit in Hangzhou, China where we discussed a range of international and domestic issues. In our bilateral relationship with Russia we regularly raise our concerns with Russia that political freedoms in that country are becoming increasingly constrained. The interests of the Russian people and the stability of the Russian state would be best served by a political system based on strong institutions, together with a safe political space for dissenting views to be heard, and free and fair elections.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May","3622","2017-07-14T12:05:37.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749480/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749480/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749480/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-07-06","Russia: Political Prisoners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, what recent discussions she has had with President Vladimir Putin of Russia on political prisoners in that country.","false","Biography information for Mr Jonathan Lord","Woking","Mr Jonathan Lord","3456"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749481","Prime Minister","false","2017-07-11","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer that I gave her on Wednesday 5 July, Official Report, column 1169.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2017-07-11T15:22:30.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749481/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749481/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749481/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-07-06","Hillsborough Stadium","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, on what date she received Bishop James Jones' report on the experience of the Hillsborough families.","false","Biography information for Alison McGovern","Wirral South","Alison McGovern","3353"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749482","Department of Health","false","2017-07-11","<p>The Government published its response to the Five Year Forward View for Mental Health on 9 January 2017. The Government accepted all recommendations set out in the report and are progressing the work as set out in the response.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2017-07-11T15:48:52.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749482/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749482/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749482/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-06","Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what progress his Department has made on implementing the recommendations in the Five Year Forward View for Mental Health.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","3344"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749483","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-11","<p>There were a total of 252 suicides on the national rail network in 2015-16.</p><p> </p><p>The figure for 2016-17 has not been released, and is due to be published on 12 July 2017.</p><p> </p><p>This figure does not include suicides on London Underground or light rail and tram networks. Figures for these networks are published at the following link: <a href="http://www.orr.gov.uk/statistics/published-stats/statistical-releases" target="_blank">http://www.orr.gov.uk/statistics/published-stats/statistical-releases</a>.</p><p> </p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-07-11T14:28:59.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749483/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749483/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749483/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-06","Railways: Suicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many people took their own life on the rail network in (a) 2015-16 and (b) 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","3345"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749484","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-14","<p>Details of the number, type, compensation levels and cost of exits from the Department for Transport are due to be published next week in the Department’s Annual Report and Accounts.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-07-14T06:15:51.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749484/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749484/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749484/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-06","Department for Transport: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many staff have left or agreed settlements to leave his Department under (a) voluntary exit, (b) voluntary redundancy and (c) compulsory redundancy since 1 November 2016; and how much compensation was paid in those cases.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","3368"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749485","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-13","<p>The number of Highways England’s Traffic Officers since 2015 is as follows:</p><p>2015: 1446</p><p>2016: 1439</p><p>2017: 1395</p><p>There has been a decrease of 51 Traffic Officers between 2015 and 2017, which equates to 3.5%.</p><p>The current total staff retention rate at Highways England is 92%, but they are not complacent. Their recruitment and selection process is being improved to include assessments that better reflect the role applicants would undertake as Traffic Officers to ensure it continues to keep and maintain sufficient staff numbers.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-07-13T12:21:32.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749485/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749485/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749485/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-06","Traffic Officers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the trend in the number of specialist road traffic officers since 2015; and what steps his Department is taking to maintain the number of specialist road traffic officers.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","3381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749486","Home Office","false","2017-07-11","<p>The Home Office does not hold information for the time period requested.</p><p> </p><p>The Home Office publishes data on the number of fixed penalty notice (FPNs) issued for ‘use of a handheld mobile phone while driving’ in the ‘Police Powers and Procedures, England and Wales’ statistical publication.</p><p> </p><p>The latest available data covers the calendar year 2015, and can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/561976/fixed-penalty-notices-police-powers-procedures-hosb1516-tables.ods" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/561976/fixed-penalty-notices-police-powers-procedures-hosb1516-tables.ods</a></p><p> </p><p>Data for the calendar year 2016 will be published in autumn 2017.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-07-11T15:54:32.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749486/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749486/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749486/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-06","Road Traffic Offences: Mobile Phones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many motorists have been penalised for using a handheld mobile telephone while driving since 1 March 2017.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","3436"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749487","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-14","<p>Following the conclusion of the consultation, the consultation responses are being processed. We are committed to responding to this consultation before the end of the year. At the time of our response, we will release the consultation details.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-07-14T05:58:26.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749487/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749487/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749487/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-06","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many responses were received in the HS2 Crewe to Manchester, West Midlands to Leeds: Route Refinement Consultation 2016; and how many of those responses were (a) in support of and (b) against the new M18 route.","false","Biography information for Edward Miliband","Doncaster North","Edward Miliband","3500"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749488","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-14","<p>The Mersey Gateway Bridge scheme is being promoted by Halton Borough Council. Annual income from tolls will vary but the most recent estimate produced for the Mersey Gateway Crossings Board shows an annual average income over the operational period of the project of £38,361,000.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-07-14T11:28:32.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749488/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749488/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749488/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-06","River Mersey: Bridges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the estimated annual income from Mersey Gateway tolls is.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","3506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749489","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-14","<p>The figure of a toll for cars of £3 was included in the Government’s consultation issued earlier in the year. The consultation set out an intention to recoup fully the costs that taxpayers have incurred outside the concession agreement, although this would take longer if the tolls were reduced.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-07-14T11:37:34.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749489/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749489/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749489/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-06","Severn River Crossing: Tolls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the estimated annual cost to the taxpayer is of reducing the Severn Bridge Toll to £3.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","3505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749490","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-14","<p>The Transport Investment Strategy sets out the priorities and principles for future investment decisions by the Department for Transport, it does not identify or decide on particular projects. We will continue to work closely with the Devolved Administrations on areas where our responsibilities interact.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-07-14T11:32:37.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749490/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749490/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749490/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-06","Transport: Infrastructure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what road and rail infrastructure projects outlined in the Transport Investment Strategy published on 5 July 2017 are considered (a) England only, (b) England and Wales, (c) England, Wales and Scotland and (d) UK-wide.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","3499"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749491","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-14","<p>The operation and funding of the Mersey Tunnels has always been a matter for the local authorities in the area. Following the creation of the Liverpool City Region Combined Authority in 2014, the ownership of the Mersey Tunnels, and the power to set tolls, rests with them. Any decision to scrap the tolls, which cover the cost of Tunnel operations and fund other local transport priorities, would therefore be for the Combined Authority to take. We have been advised by Merseytravel, which operates the Tunnels on behalf of the Combined Authority, that the Tunnel tolls currently raise £41m per year so this would represent the cost to the local taxpayer if they were foregone. In addition, if the tunnel tolls were scrapped there might well be some leakage of traffic from the Mersey Gateway bridge, which is currently under construction and will be tolled, to the tunnels. If so, this would create an adverse impact on the finances of the bridge.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-07-14T08:36:07.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749491/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749491/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749491/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-06","Mersey Tunnels: Tolls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the annual cost to the taxpayer would be of scrapping Mersey Tunnel tolls.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","3507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749492","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-12","<p>As set out in the Transport Investment Strategy, from 2020/21 the Government has guaranteed that all revenue raised from Vehicle Excise Duty (VED) in England will be allocated to a new National Roads Fund. Road infrastructure is devolved to the Welsh Government, which will receive Barnett consequentials resulting from any spending from the Fund.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-07-12T10:05:40.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749492/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749492/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749492/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-06","Excise Duties: Motor Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether vehicle excise duty raised from cars registered in Wales will be included in the National Road Fund.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","3541"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749493","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-14","<p>The relevant devolution settlements and their associated legislation determine the responsibility for infrastructure development. We continue to work closely with the Devolved Administrations (DAs) on areas where our responsibilities interact.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-07-14T11:26:57.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749493/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749493/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749493/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-06","Transport: Infrastructure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what criteria the Government uses to assess whether a transport infrastructure development is considered (a) England only, (b) England and Wales, (c) England, Wales and Scotland and (d) UK-wide.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","3530"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749494","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-14","<p>The UK Government continues to work closely with the Welsh Government to facilitate its ongoing procurement process and finalise the arrangements for the devolution of the Wales and Borders franchise. The Statutory Instrument used to transfer executive powers in relation to franchising functions is expected to be laid this autumn.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-07-14T06:06:30.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749494/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749494/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749494/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-06","Wales and Borders Rail Franchise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when the Government expects to devolve legislative powers to the Welsh Assembly to procure and manage the Wales and Borders rail franchise.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","3534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749495","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-14","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>Ministers and officials at the Department for Transport hold regular meetings with representatives of the automotive industry, and only last month the Secretary of State addressed the SMMT’s summer parliamentary reception, meeting industry stakeholders.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-07-14T11:25:14.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749495/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749495/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749495/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-06","Motor Vehicles: Manufacturing Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent discussions he has had with the automotive manufacturing industry.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","3515"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749496","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-14","<p>The Transport Investment Strategy identified that, of the £46bn programme to operate and enhance the railway between 2014-19, £30bn is for renewals and enhancements of the network infrastructure. The volumes of renewals are set out in Network Rail’s CP5 Delivery Plan 2016 update and the enhancement outputs are set out in Network Rail’s June 2017 Enhancement Delivery Plan. There is no apportionment between England and Wales.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-07-14T06:11:19.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749496/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749496/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749496/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-06","Railways: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what proportion of rail infrastructure funding identified in the Transport Investment Strategy will be spent on the Welsh rail network.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","3531"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749497","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-14","<p>Although transport issues are substantially devolved in the UK, all four Governments work together on matters where the respective infrastructure policy responsibilities of the UK government and devolved administrations overlap.</p><p> </p><p>The Transport Investment Strategy sets out principles for future investment decisions, including as to the balance between the need to keep decision-making as close as possible to the people affected and the need to ensure the coherence and integrity of national networks. We will continue to work closely with the Devolved Administrations on areas of mutual interest, for example on long-distance rail lines such as the East and West Coast Mainlines, or HS2.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-07-14T11:20:18.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749497/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749497/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749497/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-06","Transport: Infrastructure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what mechanisms will be put in place to ensure effective consultation with the devolved administrations on proposals made in the Transport Investment Strategy.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","3532"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749498","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-14","<p>Although transport issues are substantially devolved in the UK, all four Governments work closely on areas where THEIR interests and responsibilities interact. While we have not yet received representations directly from the Welsh Assembly on the Transport Investment Strategy, we will continue to work closely with the Devolved Administrations on areas of mutual interest and TO consider any representations they may make as part of that dialogue.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-07-14T11:43:08.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749498/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749498/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749498/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-06","Transport: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what representations the Government has received from the Welsh Assembly on the Transport Investment Strategy.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","3533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749499","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-13","<p>The National Roads Fund will commence in 2020-21. The Barnett Formula will be applied in the normal way when allocations are made from the Fund.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-07-13T11:51:38.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749499/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749499/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749499/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-06","Roads: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the Barnett consequential the Welsh Assembly will receive with the implementation of the National Road Fund.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","3542"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749500","Wales Office","false","2017-07-14","<p>The Wales Office prioritises low-cost and no-cost methods of communication to maximise impact at minimal cost to the taxpayer. The majority of our social media is done through owned and earned channels.</p><p> </p><p>The Department spent £71 on limited targeted communications activity aimed at potential exporters ahead of a UK Export Summit in Cardiff. Paid for social media marketing over the past twelve months was to augment our direct communications, digital communications and media relations activity ahead of the UK Export Summit in Cardiff.</p><p> </p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2017-07-14T09:27:09.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749500/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749500/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749500/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-07-06","Wales Office: Advertising","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how much his Department has spent on advertising on social media in each month since January 2016.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","3414"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749501","Wales Office","false","2017-07-14","<p>Passengers rightly expect high quality rail services and from Autumn 2017, passengers in Wales will benefit from the new generation of electric trains which will deliver 27% more seats, faster journey times and improved connectivity for South Wales to London with 40% more seats in the morning peak once the full fleet is in service.</p><p> </p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2017-07-14T13:34:59.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749501/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749501/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749501/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-07-06","South Wales Railway Line: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what the timetable is for the completion of the electrification of the Cardiff to Swansea railway line.","false","Biography information for Chris Elmore","Ogmore","Chris Elmore","3379"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749502","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-12","<p>Government provides a range of guidance on the provision of flexible hours, including for mothers returning to work. This includes guidance on the GOV.UK website covering what employers have to do, types of flexible working, the statutory application process and appeals. ACAS also provides advice and guidance.</p><p>As we said in response to the Women &amp; Equalities Select Committee report on the gender pay gap, the Government recognises the need to increase communications activity around flexible working and will explore options for doing so.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-12T11:10:25.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749502/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749502/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749502/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-06","Working Mothers: Flexible Working","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what guidance the Government provides to employers on the provision of flexible hours for mothers returning to work.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","3419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749503","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-12","<p>The Department meets regularly with business organisations to discuss a range of issues including those which can impact upon the gender pay gap. Consultations in 2015 and 2016 on the gender pay gap have emphasised that fully capitalising on the talent and experience of women makes business sense; it is good for individuals, employers and the economy.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-12T11:10:37.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749503/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749503/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749503/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-06","Equal Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions he has had with business organisations on the implications of maternity leave and requests for flexible working for the gender pay gap.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","3420"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749504","Women and Equalities","false","2017-07-14","<p>We are proud that we legislated for the introduction of marriage for same sex couples.</p><p>It is already possible for same sex couples in a civil partnership to convert their civil partnership to a marriage in the parts of the United Kingdom where same sex marriage is legal.</p><p>There were 7,732 couples in England and Wales who chose to convert their existing civil partnership into a marriage between 10 December 2014 and 30 June 2015 (just over six months of data).</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-07-14T13:06:27.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749504/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749504/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749504/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-07-06","Marriage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, if she will take steps to amend same-sex marriage legislation to allow couples to convert civil partnerships to marriage.","false","Biography information for Angela Crawley","Lanark and Hamilton East","Angela Crawley","3446"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749505","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-11","<p>The decision was made in 1995 to equalise the State Pension age for men and women. This addressed a longstanding inequality in pension age. If State Pension ages had not been equalised, women would be spending over 40% of their adult life in retirement. Men’s and women’s State Pension age will equalise in November 2018.</p><p> </p><p>The new State Pension is much more generous for many women, who have been historically worse off under the old system. By 2030, over 3 million women stand to gain an average of £550 extra per year as a result of recent changes.</p><p> </p><p>Automatic enrolment into workplace pensions was designed to help more people save for their retirement, including groups who historically have been less likely to save, such as women and lower earners. In 2012, overall workplace participation by eligible female employees was 58 per cent, compared to male participation at 52 per cent but since the introduction of automatic enrolment, the participation of female eligible employees has increased to 80 per cent in 2016 with overall male participation at 76 per cent.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the current review of automatic enrolment, the Government has committed to look at the existing coverage of the policy and consider the needs of those not currently benefiting from automatic enrolment. The review will have regard to the Equality Act, as well as the need to balance the needs of individual savers, with affordability for employers and value for money for tax payers.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-07-11T15:52:52.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749505/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749505/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749505/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-06","Pension Rights: Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he will take to eliminate inequalities in pension rights.","false","Biography information for Angela Crawley","Lanark and Hamilton East","Angela Crawley","3448"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749506","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-13","<p>Inflammatory bowel disease is a term commonly used to refer either Crohn’s disease or Ulcerative Colitis. The available information is shown in the following tables:</p><p> </p><p><strong>Table 1: Number of individuals making an initial claim to Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) whose main disabling condition was recorded as Crohn’s Disease or Ulcerative Colitis, Great Britain, 2014 - 2016</strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong> Year of ESA claim start</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Initial ESA<br> claims</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p>2,800</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p>2,600</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2016 (Jan - Sep)</strong></p></td><td><p>1,800</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong>Table 2: Number of individuals assigned to the ESA Support Group or the ESA Work Capability Group following their Work Capability Assessment (for initial, repeat or IB reassessment claims), whose main disabling condition was recorded as Crohn’s Disease or Ulcerative Colitis, Great Britain, 2014 - 2016</strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year of ESA claim start </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Initial ESA<br> claims</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Repeat ESA<br> assessments</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>IB<br> reassessments</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p>1,200</p></td><td><p>400</p></td><td><p>200</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p>1,200</p></td><td><p>300</p></td><td><p>100</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2016 (Jan - Sep)</strong></p></td><td><p>700</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong>Source for Tables 1 and 2:</strong> Application data is derived from administrative data held by the DWP and assessment data provided by the Healthcare Provider.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Notes for Tables 1 and 2:</strong></p><ol><li>The figures are rounded to the nearest 100. – denotes figures that are zero or less than 50.</li><li>The information for 2016 is provided up to September 2016 only; this is the latest data available at time of request.</li><li>An individual may have made more than one ESA claim or assessment in any given year. These individuals will only be counted once in each of the figures provided.</li><li>The primary medical condition recorded on the claim form does not itself confer entitlement to ESA. So, for example, a decision on entitlement for a customer claiming ESA on the basis of Crohn’s disease or Ulcerative Colitis would be based on their ability to carry out the range of activities assessed by the work capability assessment.</li></ol>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-07-13T10:23:43.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749506/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749506/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749506/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-06","Employment and Support Allowance: Inflammatory Bowel Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people have (a) applied for and (b) received employment and support allowance for inflammatory bowel disease in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","3518"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749507","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-12","<p>DWP Corporate Services has a contract with CARAT LTD for Media Buying services which covers Social Media advertising. The amount spent for the period stated amounts to an average of £21k per month.</p><p> </p><p>A more precise and detailed response could only be extracted at disproportionate cost.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-07-12T14:09:06.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749507/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749507/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749507/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-06","Department for Work and Pensions: Advertising","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much his Department has spent on advertising on social media in each month since January 2016.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","3415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749508","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-13","<p>At 30 November 2016 the number of Employment and Support Allowance claimants with Motor Neurone Disease as their primary medical condition in the Work-Related Activity Group and the Support Group was 10 and 640 respectively.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-07-13T10:09:05.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749508/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749508/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749508/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-06","Employment and Support Allowance: Motor Neurone Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many employment and support allowance claimants with motor neurone disease are in (a) the work related activity group and (b) support group; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","3475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749509","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-13","<p>The Health Professional is not required to diagnose a condition or to recommend treatment options. Instead it requires the Health Professional to look at the impact the condition or impairment has on a claimants’ daily life. This requires very different skills from those involved in the diagnosis and treatment of their patients, with less need for specialist knowledge on diagnosis and treatment.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Work Capability Assessment is a functional assessment which focuses on what an individual can do, rather than assuming that their health condition or disability automatically means they can’t work.</p><p> </p><p>The assessment for Personal Independence Payment focuses on a claimant’s ability to carry out a range of activities which are fundamental to living an independent life. It is designed to help working age people with the extra costs associated with their disability.</p><p> </p><p>All the assessment providers are committed to continuous improvement to support a more consistent application of the assessment process. In addition, the Providers frequently engage with medical experts, charities and relevant stakeholders to strengthen review and update training programmes for all their assessment staff.</p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-07-13T10:43:38.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749509/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749509/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749509/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-06","Social Security Benefits: Inflammatory Bowel Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps the Government is taking to ensure employment and support allowance and personal independence payment assessments take greater account of the complexities of inflammatory bowel disease.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","3578"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749510","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-13","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>The requested information for the number of Personal Independence Payment (PIP) applications for people with inflammatory bowel disease is not available because information on PIP claimants’ disabling conditions is not collected at the initial claim application stage.</p><p> </p><p>The number of people in receipt of PIP with a main disabling condition of inflammatory bowel disease is 5,100, as at the 30<sup>th</sup> April 2017 and has been published at the following link. Please see the tables “Personal Independence Payment: Detailed medical condition, April 2017 caseload” and filter by ‘Inflammatory bowel disease on the subgroup category. This publication is updated quarterly.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/personal-independence-payment-april-2013-to-april-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/personal-independence-payment-april-2013-to-april-2017</a></p><p> </p><p>Data is based on primary disabling condition as recorded on the PIP computer system. Claimants may often have multiple disabling conditions upon which the decision is based but only the primary condition is shown in these statistics. Therefore, there may be other claimants in receipt of PIP who have been diagnosed with inflammatory bowel disease who are not captured in the data.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-07-13T10:48:10.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749510/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749510/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749510/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-06","Personal Independence Payment: Inflammatory Bowel Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people have (a) applied for and (b) received personal independence payments support from his Department related to inflammatory bowel disease.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","3579"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749511","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-11","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>There is no condition based entitlement to Employment Support Allowance.</p><p> </p><p>Rather than a list of specific medical conditions, the criteria will be based on identifying claimants with the most severe health conditions or disabilities where it would be unreasonable to expect the individual to undertake any form or amount of work or work-related activity.</p><p> </p><p>This change will come into effect in autumn 2017 and will apply to those placed in Employment and Support Allowance’s Support Group and the Universal Credit equivalent.</p><p> </p><p>We are currently working with stakeholders to develop the new criteria and, when finalised, the amended guidance will be incorporated into the Work Capability Assessment Handbook published annually on GOV.UK. This change will be reflected in the summer 2018 update.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-07-11T12:03:27.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749511/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749511/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749511/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-06","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, on what date he plans to publish the list of long-term and life-limiting diseases that will be exempt from benefit re-assessments.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","3587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749512","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-11","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>This Government remains dedicated to improving employment outcomes for people with disabilities and long-term health conditions. The Government has committed itself to getting 1 million more disabled people into work over the next ten years.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-07-11T11:51:03.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749512/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749512/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749512/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-06","Employment: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether it is his policy to halve the disability employment gap by 2030.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","3585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749513","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-13","<p>We have no plans to change the current policy of not paying benefit during the Mandatory Reconsideration process.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-07-13T10:28:03.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749513/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749513/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749513/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-06","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will extend assessment rate payments to claimants of employment and support allowance who are waiting for the outcome of a mandatory reconsideration.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","3527"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749514","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-11","<p>The Government published the Work, Health and Disability Green Paper (Improving Lives) in October 2016. The Government is currently reviewing over 6000 responses that were received as part of a national consultation, is considering next steps and will respond in due course.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-07-11T11:57:26.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749514/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749514/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749514/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-06","Employment: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, on what date he plans to publish the White Paper on Work, Health and Disability.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","3586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749515","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-14","<p>The Government wants all disabled people and people with a long term health condition, including those with inflammatory bowel syndrome, to have the opportunity to work and share in the economic and health benefits that work brings.</p><p> </p><p>Government supports employers to help them recruit and retain people with health conditions and disabilities through the Disability Confident campaign, Fit for Work and the Access to Work scheme.</p><p> </p><p>We published ‘Improving Lives the Work: Health and Disability Green Paper’ in October, and we are analysing the responses to understand how employers can be further supported to establish good practices and supportive workplace cultures, and how they can support more people with disabilities and health conditions to stay in or return to work.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-07-14T13:56:05.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749515/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749515/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749515/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-06","Inflammatory Bowel Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to raise awareness of inflammatory bowel disease and its effects with employers.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","3519"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749516","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-14","<p>Automatic enrolment is a policy that works. Over 8 million individuals have been automatically enrolled into a workplace pension by more than 640,000 employers.</p><p> </p><p>Since 2012 private sector employment has grown by 2.6 million to reach 26.5 million. Automatic enrolment has been implemented on a national basis rather than being trialled which means it is not possible to make any assessment of the effect on the level of private sector job creation.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman","3370","2017-07-14T11:57:17.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749516/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749516/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749516/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-06","Occupational Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effect of compulsory workplace pensions on the level of private sector job creation since 2012.","false","Biography information for Mr Jonathan Lord","Woking","Mr Jonathan Lord","3461"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749517","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-14","<p>Employees of the Department for Work and Pensions do not undertake Employment and Support Allowance or Personal Independence Payment assessments.</p><p> </p><p>In August 2012 following a competitive tendering exercise the contract for undertaking Personal Independence Payment assessments was awarded to Atos Healthcare and Capita Business Services Ltd.</p><p> </p><p>Work Capability Assessments are delivered through the Health and Disability Assessment Service Contract. It is a three year contract from March 2015 delivered by the Centre for Health and Disability Assessments, a subsidiary of MAXIMUS.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-07-14T13:56:27.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749517/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749517/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749517/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-06","Department for Work and Pensions: Disciplinary Proceedings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many employees of his Department have been referred for disciplinary action as a result of factual inaccuracies in employment and support allowance and personal independence payment assessments in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","3374"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749518","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-13","<p>Since 1 November 2016 the Department has released the following number of exits under the required categories</p><p> </p><p>a) Voluntary exit, 2</p><p>b) Voluntary redundancy, 0</p><p>c) Compulsory redundancy, 0</p><p> </p><p>The amount of compensation paid totalled £144,000.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-07-13T11:46:16.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749518/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749518/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749518/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-06","Department for Work and Pensions: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many staff have left or agreed settlements to leave his Department under (a) voluntary exit, (b) voluntary redundancy and (c) compulsory redundancy since 1 November 2016; and how much compensation was paid in those cases.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","3369"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749519","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-13","<p>Strict audit and quality control measures are in place to ensure the Centre for Health and Disability Assessments delivers high-quality assessments.</p><p> </p><p>The Department introduced the independent audit of Work Capability Assessments in March 2015 in line with the start of the new Health and Disability Assessment Service contract. Audit has a central role in confirming that independent health professional advice complies with the required standards and that it is clear and medically reasonable. It also provides assurance that any approach to assessment and opinion given is consistent so that, irrespective of where or by whom the assessment is carried out, claimants with conditions that have the same functional effect will ultimately receive the same benefit outcome.</p><p> </p><p>Health Professionals receive training on how to identify the impact of mental health conditions on claimants. This is followed by on-going professional training and support which continues for the duration of their employment in the role.</p><p> </p><p>Providers are required to make every attempt to obtain the best evidence available to assist the Health Professional undertaking the assessment to make a fully formed judgment. This includes evidence from Community Mental Health Teams, psychologists, psychiatrists and social workers supporting claimants with mental health conditions.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-07-13T10:05:25.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749519/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749519/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749519/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-06","Work Capability Assessment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent assessment he has made of the effectiveness of health capability assessments for claimants of employment and support allowance with (a) mental health issues and (b) learning difficulties.","false","Biography information for Mr Jonathan Lord","Woking","Mr Jonathan Lord","3372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749520","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-14","<p>Automatic enrolment is a policy that works. Over 8 million individuals have been automatically enrolled into a workplace pension by more than 640,000 employers.</p><p> </p><p>Since 2012 private sector employment has grown by 2.6 million to reach 26.5 million. Automatic enrolment has been implemented on a national basis rather than being trialled which means it is not possible to make any assessment of the effect on the level of private sector job creation.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman","3461","2017-07-14T11:57:17.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749520/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749520/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749520/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-06","Occupational Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effect of compulsory workplace pensions on the level of private sector job creation since the introduction of those pensions in 2012.","false","Biography information for Mr Jonathan Lord","Woking","Mr Jonathan Lord","3370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749521","Department for Education","false","2017-07-13","<p>The table below shows the numbers of women born between 6 April 1950 and 31 December 1959 who have started and achieved an apprenticeship in the last five academic years:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="5"><p><strong>Academic year</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>2011/12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014/15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015/16</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Starts</strong></p></td><td><p>14,000</p></td><td><p>11,500</p></td><td><p>6,800</p></td><td><p>7,500</p></td><td><p>6,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Achievements</strong></p></td><td><p>6,800</p></td><td><p>6,700</p></td><td><p>5,100</p></td><td><p>3,900</p></td><td><p>3,500</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Please note: for apprenticeship starts and achievements, age is calculated based on age at the start of the programme rather than based on 31 August of the academic year but does not include 16/17 figures.</p><p>Data on apprenticeship starts and achievements by age band, and by gender are available in the apprenticeship demographic tools:</p><p>Starts: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/624584/apprenticeships-demographics-data-tool-starts-v1.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/624584/apprenticeships-demographics-data-tool-starts-v1.xlsx</a>.</p><p>Achievements:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/624824/apprenticeships-demographics-data-tool-achievements-v1.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/624824/apprenticeships-demographics-data-tool-achievements-v1.xlsx</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-07-13T15:33:20.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749521/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749521/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749521/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-06","State Retirement Pensions: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many women born in the 1950s and affected by the change in the state pension age have (a) taken up and (b) completed apprenticeships.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","3303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749522","Department for Education","false","2017-07-13","<p>In the 2017 Budget, £5 million was allocated to increase the number of programmes for returners in the public and private sector. The Government Equalities Office is developing programmes to support people who want to return to the workplace. These have not yet been launched but will be open to all those who wish to return to paid work, having taken time out of the labour market for caring. This includes women born in the 1950s and affected by the change in the state pension age.</p><p> </p><p>The number of older workers in employment is at a record high, this includes 1.2 million workers over the age of 65. This corresponds to an increase in the employment rate for individuals over the age of 65 from 6.7% to 10.3% over the past ten years. The Government is keen in supporting older people to return to the labour market and that is why we invested £1.6 million in nine pilots across England to explore ways to support carers to balance work and caring responsibilities. The final evaluation report is expected later this Summer.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-07-13T15:39:32.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749522/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749522/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749522/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-06","State Retirement Pensions: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many women born in the 1950s and affected by the change in the state pension age have successfully taken part in the returner's scheme to return to the workplace.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","3304"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749523","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-14","<p>The number of older workers in the UK is at a record high, currently standing at 9.9m workers aged 50 years and over. 4.2m women aged 50-64 are in employment; this compares to 3.5m five years ago. There are 1.2 million individuals in employment aged over 65, of which 39% are women.</p><p> </p><p>Employment rates for older workers have also been increasing and recently reached record highs. Since ten years ago, the employment rate has increased by 6.0 percentage points (pp) (from 65.0% to 71.0%) for people aged 50-64. The current employment rate for women aged 50-64 is at a record high of 66.4%.</p><p> </p><p>Further information on estimates of employment, unemployment, economic inactivity and other employment-related statistics for the UK can be found in the “UK labour market: July 2017” statistical bulletin published at the Office for National Statistics (ONS) website:</p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/employmentandemployeetypes/bulletins/uklabourmarket/july2017" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/employmentandemployeetypes/bulletins/uklabourmarket/july2017</a></p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to supporting people aged 50 years and over to remain in and return to work; the ‘Fuller Working Lives: A Partnership Approach’ strategy was published on 2nd February. This, crucially, is led by employers, but it also sets out the case for action by individuals, and the role of Government in supporting them in planning their careers and their approach to retirement. The Strategy and supporting evidence base are available at the attached web address:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/fuller-working-lives-a-partnership-approach" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/fuller-working-lives-a-partnership-approach</a></p><p> </p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman","3302","2017-07-14T11:55:11.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749523/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749523/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749523/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-06","State Retirement Pensions: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many women born in the 1950s and affected by the change in the state pension age have been able to return to employment from a position of unemployment.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","3305"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749524","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-14","<p>The number of older workers in the UK is at a record high, currently standing at 9.9m workers aged 50 years and over. 4.2m women aged 50-64 are in employment; this compares to 3.5m five years ago. There are 1.2 million individuals in employment aged over 65, of which 39% are women.</p><p> </p><p>Employment rates for older workers have also been increasing and recently reached record highs. Since ten years ago, the employment rate has increased by 6.0 percentage points (pp) (from 65.0% to 71.0%) for people aged 50-64. The current employment rate for women aged 50-64 is at a record high of 66.4%.</p><p> </p><p>Further information on estimates of employment, unemployment, economic inactivity and other employment-related statistics for the UK can be found in the “UK labour market: July 2017” statistical bulletin published at the Office for National Statistics (ONS) website:</p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/employmentandemployeetypes/bulletins/uklabourmarket/july2017" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/employmentandemployeetypes/bulletins/uklabourmarket/july2017</a></p><p> </p><p>The Government is committed to supporting people aged 50 years and over to remain in and return to work; the ‘Fuller Working Lives: A Partnership Approach’ strategy was published on 2nd February. This, crucially, is led by employers, but it also sets out the case for action by individuals, and the role of Government in supporting them in planning their careers and their approach to retirement. The Strategy and supporting evidence base are available at the attached web address:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/fuller-working-lives-a-partnership-approach" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/fuller-working-lives-a-partnership-approach</a></p><p> </p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman","3305","2017-07-14T11:55:10.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749524/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749524/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749524/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-06","State Retirement Pensions: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many women born in the 1950s and affected by the change in the state pension age have not been able to return to employment.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","3302"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749525","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-13","<p>The Department robustly monitors the performance of contracted suppliers and assessments are independently audited to ensure that the advice provided to the Department’s decision makers is of suitable quality, fully explained and justified. Assessment reports deemed unacceptable are returned to the provider for reworking. We continue to work extensively with PIP assessment providers to make improvements to guidance, training and audit procedures in order to ensure a quality service is maintained.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Detailed guidance on how reports are audited and the criteria to be used are set out in section 4.5 of the Personal Independence Payment Assessment Guide, which can be found here <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/547146/pip-assessment-guide.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/547146/pip-assessment-guide.pdf</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Both assessment providers are committed to continuous improvement. We are examining the merits of audio-recording face-to-face assessments to support a more consistent application of the assessment process and also changes to the way information is gathered during the assessment.</p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-07-13T10:38:32.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749525/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749525/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749525/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-06","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how the performance of PIP assessors is monitored.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","3568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749526","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-14","<p>There are no plans in place to include copies of the assessors’ reports before assessment decisions are made</p><p> </p><p>One of Paul Gray’s recommendations following his recent review of PIP Assessments was to share copies of assessors' reports with individual claimants with their decision letter. We are currently considering all 14 of Paul Gray’s recommendations and plan to respond later this year.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-07-14T13:56:42.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749526/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749526/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749526/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-06","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make it his policy to share copies of assessors' reports with individual claimants before decisions on personal independence payment claims are made.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","3565"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749527","Department for Education","false","2017-07-13","<p>The Higher Education Statistics Agency (HESA) collects and publishes statistics on students enrolled at UK Higher Education Institutions (HEIs). Annual statistics on higher education students are published at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.hesa.ac.uk/data-and-analysis/statistical-first-releases%20" target="_blank">https://www.hesa.ac.uk/data-and-analysis/statistical-first-releases</a>.</p><p> </p><p>In academic year 2015/16 there were five undergraduate and 25 postgraduate students of Cuban domicile enrolled at UK HEIs.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-07-13T14:08:12.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749527/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749527/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749527/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-06","Overseas Students: Cuba","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many (a) undergraduate and (b) postgraduate students studying in the UK are of Cuban nationality.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","3548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749528","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-11","<p>The Higher Education Funding Council for England (HEFCE) is a non-departmental public body with statutory independence from Ministers. Detailed and specific funding decisions are therefore entirely a matter for HEFCE. In this instance, HEFCE issued a competitive call into which universities across the UK were invited to submit bids for science capital funding. All bids were evaluated by an independent expert assessment panel against clearly defined, published criteria, including a requirement that bids should be built on a strong record of research excellence and should leverage co-investment from non-public sources at a ratio of at least 2:1.</p><p> </p><p>The University of Sheffield’s bid for a “Steel Research and Testing Centre” did not meet all of the criteria on this occasion. A further funding round will open in the Autumn, and the University may submit a revised bid.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-07-11T09:03:09.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749528/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749528/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749528/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-06","Sheffield University: Iron and Steel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the effect of the decision by the Higher Education Funding Council for England not to fund the Advanced Structured Testing Centre at Sheffield University on the UK steel industry; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","3549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749529","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-12","<p>HM Treasury has made no assessment of the relationship between household spending and business sustainability.</p><p> </p><p>The government is supporting business by cutting Corporation Tax to 17% - the lowest rate in the G20; providing over £23bn in additional investment in economic infrastructure, research and development, and housing; and through the Industrial Strategy, which will increase productivity and drive growth across the whole country.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-07-12T09:24:59.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749529/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749529/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749529/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-06","Consumers: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect of reductions in household spending power on the economic sustainability of businesses of all sizes in (a) the retail sector and (b) the service sector.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","3325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749530","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-12","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring competitive and affordable energy costs for all businesses as well as households. The Committee on Climate Change recently assessed energy costs for all businesses and concluded that energy costs are a small proportion of businesses’ operating costs.</p><p>In their final report on the investigation into the energy markets published in June 2016, the Competition Markets Authority proposed a number of remedies to help microbusinesses access better energy deals. The Government supports the implementation of these measures which have now been implemented by Ofgem. These will improve the transparency of tariffs available to businesses and by making it easier for these businesses to switch suppliers.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-12T12:39:31.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749530/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749530/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749530/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-06","Energy: Small Businesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the effect of energy prices on the viability of small and medium-sized businesses.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","3324"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749531","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-11","<p>The Department has made no such assessment. The effect of any extension of the safeguard tariff would depend on the number of customers who are eligible and the level at which the cap is set. This is a matter for Ofgem, which is currently considering options, including extending the current safeguard tariff.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-07-11T14:21:17.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749531/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749531/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749531/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-06","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate his Department has made of the potential reduction in the domestic energy market consumer detriment to be achieved by implementing an extension of the pre-payment meter safeguard tariff to those eligible for Warm Home Discount who have a credit meter.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","3335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749532","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-11","<p>Ofgem is subject to a duty under the Gas Act (1986) and Electricity Act (1989), to consider the interests of consumers who might be considered vulnerable in the domestic energy market. These include those who are disabled, chronically sick, elderly, on low income or live in rural areas.</p><p>Ofgem are also able to take into account the needs of other groups of consumers who may be vulnerable.</p><p>Ofgem’s Consumer Vulnerability Strategy is available online at:</p><p><a href="https://www.ofgem.gov.uk/ofgem-publications/75550/consumer-vulnerability-strategy-pdf" target="_blank">https://www.ofgem.gov.uk/ofgem-publications/75550/consumer-vulnerability-strategy-pdf</a></p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-11T15:23:11.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749532/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749532/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749532/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-06","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how his Department defines a vulnerable customer in the domestic energy market.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","3336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749533","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-13","<p>The CEO of Ofgem wrote to my right hon. Friend the Secretary of State on 3 July setting out his intention to consider options to protect vulnerable consumers including extending the protection in place for pre-payment meter customers. In the letter Ofgem stated it will move forward urgently to implement any changes. As a first step Ofgem plans to hold a summit with consumers groups this month.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-07-13T13:17:32.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749533/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749533/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749533/answer","Watford","Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749533/answer/previousversion/3666","Biography information for Richard Harrington","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-06","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what representations he has had from Ofgem on the timescale for the (a) publication of measures to protect vulnerable consumers with an extension of the pre-payment meter safeguard tariff and (b) implementation of such measures; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","3337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749534","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-12","<p>Ofgem has wide powers under the Gas Act 1986 and the Electricity Act 1989 to modify the conditions of gas and electricity supply licences, which would allow for the introduction of a domestic energy price cap.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-12T15:25:32.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749534/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749534/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749534/answer","Stourbridge","Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749534/answer/previousversion/3667","Biography information for Margot James","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-06","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what scope Ofgem has to implement a domestic energy market price cap without the need for further primary legislation.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","3338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749535","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-11","<p>Great Britain has one of the largest and most competitive wholesale gas hubs in the world and British retail gas prices are amongst the lowest in Europe. We benefit from highly diverse and flexible sources of gas supply, including storage, indigenous production, six international gas pipelines with Norway, Belgium and the Netherlands and three liquefied natural gas terminals.</p><p>In addition, increased competition in the retail gas market means that households now having a choice of around 55 companies supplying gas. Smaller suppliers are continuing to grow their market share and now have just over 18% of the domestic retail gas market. Nevertheless the Government considers that domestic standard variable tariff customers are being charged unjustifiably high prices – as confirmed by the Competition and Markets Authority investigation into the energy market.</p><p>In addition Ofgem has said it will consider extending the price cap in place for customers on pre-payment meters to more vulnerable customers.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-11T16:24:40.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749535/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749535/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749535/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-06","Natural Gas: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to reduce the cost of gas energy to customers.","false","Biography information for John McNally","Falkirk","John McNally","3331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749536","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-12","<p>There have not been any discussions between this department and my right hon. Friend the Minister for the Cabinet Office recently, on this specific subject. Large businesses have, since April this year, been subject to a twice yearly statutory duty to report to Government on their payment practices and performance. The first reports will be due from October this year, depending on the relevant business’s financial year.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-12T15:47:00.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749536/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749536/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749536/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-06","Business: Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions he has had with the Minister for the Cabinet Office on regulation relating to late payment of invoices by businesses.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","3326"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749537","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-11","<p>The Department is not currently aware of which stakeholders the independent regulator Ofgem plans to meet with, to discuss proposals for increased price protections in domestic energy markets.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-11T15:23:39.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749537/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749537/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749537/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-06","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what information his Department holds on which stakeholders Ofgem plans to meet to discuss formulation of proposals for increased price protection in domestic energy markets.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","3339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749538","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-11","<p>There has been significant investment in the UK’s natural gas supply infrastructure over the last decade. As a result we benefit from highly diverse and flexible sources of natural gas. These include indigenous production from the North Sea; six international gas pipelines with Norway, Belgium and the Netherlands; three Liquefied Natural Gas terminals that can bring gas from anywhere in the world; and a number of modern, responsive gas storage facilities. We are confident that market-led investment will continue to deliver secure gas supplies.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-07-11T08:45:03.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749538/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749538/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749538/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-06","Natural Gas: Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to improve the storage capacity of the gas grid.","false","Biography information for John McNally","Falkirk","John McNally","3330"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749539","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-11","<p>The UK Government supports shale gas exploration to determine the potential of the industry. Shale gas is natural gas found deep underground in impermeable shale rock and requires hydraulic fracturing (or ‘fracking’) to flow.</p><p> </p><p>Shale gas could create a new British industry, provide more jobs and make us less reliant on imports from abroad. However, we are clear: shale gas operations will only take place in a manner which is safe for the environment and local communities.</p><p> </p><p>Any company looking to develop shale will need to obtain all the necessary permissions, including planning and environmental permits, before hydraulic fracturing can be carried out.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-07-11T14:32:15.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749539/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749539/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749539/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-06","Fracking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what his Department's policy is on fracking.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","3323"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749540","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-12","<p>Within the Cabinet, my Rt Hon Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy has responsibility for matters of energy policy.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-07-12T10:02:06.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749540/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749540/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749540/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-06","Tidal Power: Swansea Bay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, which members of the Cabinet will be responsible for making a decision on the pathfinder tidal lagoon in Swansea Bay.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","3388"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749541","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-11","<p>Small businesses are vital to our economy and so it is important we do all we can to make the UK a great place to start and grow a business.</p><p>Government has actively supported and invested in the creation of a network of Growth Hubs to provide businesses with tailored advice and support at the local level.</p><p>In the West Midlands, including Coventry, this is delivered by six Local Enterprise Partnership led Growth Hubs. The Business Support helpline also provides information and guidance over the phone, via email, webchat and social media.</p><p>To stimulate innovation and growth in the region, Innovate UK in 2016-17 committed almost £36.1m to 110 projects for SMEs based in the West Midlands.</p><p>In addition, the soon to be launched Midlands Engine Investment Fund, aims to boost the region’s economy and support the growth ambitions of its smaller businesses. It will facilitate investment of over £250 million across the region to help SMEs to achieve their growth ambitions, revitalise local economies and create jobs.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-11T10:43:46.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749541/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749541/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749541/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-06","Small Businesses: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to support small business growth in (a) the West Midlands and (b) Coventry.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","3439"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749542","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-14","<p>Yes, BEIS officials are working closely with the UK automotive industry to understand the impacts and opportunities of leaving the EU. The Government will continue its longstanding programme of support for the competitiveness of the UK automotive industry, including pursuing a bold and ambitious Free Trade Agreement with the EU that provides the greatest possible tariff free and frictionless trade in goods and services.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-07-14T13:39:06.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749542/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749542/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749542/answer","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749542/answer/previousversion/3665","Biography information for Claire Perry","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-06","Motor Vehicles: Manufacturing Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, with reference to the Answer of 25 October 2016 to Question HL2367, on motor vehicles, if it remains his Department's policy to support all UK-based or manufacturers and ensure that their ability to export is not adversely affected when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","3435"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749543","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-14","<p>Since January 2016, the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills, the Department for Energy and Climate Change and the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy have spent the following amount on social media<strong>.</strong></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong><em>Date</em></strong></p></td><td><p><strong><em>Spend</em></strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January 2016</p></td><td><p>£10,979</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>February 2016</p></td><td><p>£40,466</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>March 2016</p></td><td><p>£132,073</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April 2016</p></td><td><p>£37,610</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>May 2016</p></td><td><p>£33,291</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>June 2016</p></td><td><p>£40,364</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>July 2016</p></td><td><p>£9,383</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>August 2016</p></td><td><p>£42,983</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>September 2016</p></td><td><p>£13,107</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>October 2016</p></td><td><p>£19,016</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>November 2016</p></td><td><p>£12,046</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>December 2016</p></td><td><p>£10,880</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January 2017</p></td><td><p>£12,116</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>February 2017</p></td><td><p>£11,678</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>March 2017</p></td><td><p>£130,717</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April 2017</p></td><td><p>£136,318</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>May 2017</p></td><td><p>£0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>June 2017</p></td><td><p>£0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>These figures represent gross social media advertising spend excluding fees, commission and VAT. ‘Social’ channels are defined as Facebook, Instagram, LinkedIn, Snapchat (traded as display) and Twitter. These figures represent total spend for each month by DECC, BIS and now BEIS since January 2016.</p><p> </p><p>Government advertising supports the government’s priorities and helps deliver its programmes, from raising awareness of the National Minimum and Living Wage, to encouraging young people to apply for apprenticeships. The media in which we place government advertising are selected for their ability to most effectively reach our target audience.</p><p> </p><p>Government advertising is purchased by our media buying partner, Carat. Carat has held the contract for UK government media buying since January 2015.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-14T11:02:37.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749543/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749543/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749543/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-06","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Advertising","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much his Department has spent on advertising on social media in each month since January 2016.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","3400"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749544","Department for Education","false","2017-07-17","<p>In the 2015 to 2016 academic year, 3,030 women aged 60 and over participated in an apprenticeship. Between August 2016 and April 2017, 3,470 women have participated in an apprenticeship.</p><p>Data on apprenticeship starts and achievements by age band and by gender are available in the apprenticeship demographic tools:</p><p>Starts:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/624584/apprenticeships-demographics-data-tool-starts-v1.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/624584/apprenticeships-demographics-data-tool-starts-v1.xlsx</a>.</p><p>Achievements:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/624824/apprenticeships-demographics-data-tool-achievements-v1.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/624824/apprenticeships-demographics-data-tool-achievements-v1.xlsx</a>.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-07-17T17:01:16.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749544/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749544/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749544/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-06","Apprentices: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many women over the age of 60 are currently undertaking an apprenticeship.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","3504"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749545","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-13","<p>We have frequent conversations with key stakeholders in the automotive sector, including through our partnership with the Automotive Council.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-07-13T16:18:08.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749545/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749545/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749545/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-06","Motor Vehicles: Manufacturing Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent discussions he has had with the automotive manufacturing industry.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","3512"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749546","Department for Education","false","2017-07-17","<p>In the 2015 to 2016 academic year, the average (mean) age of women participating in apprenticeships was 29.2 years old. Between August 2016 and April 2017, the average (mean) age of women reported to be participating was 29.8 years old.</p><p>Please note: age is reported as at 31 August of the academic year.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-07-17T17:03:25.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749546/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749546/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749546/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-06","Apprentices: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the average age is of women undertaking apprenticeships.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","3517"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749547","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-11","<p>British Business Bank programmes are supporting finance to smaller businesses, with one of the main programmes administered by the Start-Up Loans Company. As of 31<sup>st </sup>May 2017, there were 68 start-up loans worth £493,000 in the Coventry South constituency.</p><p>Micro-enterprises in the Coventry South constituency have access to the Coventry &amp; Warwickshire Growth Hub which can provide tailored advice and support. The Business Support helpline also provides information and guidance over the phone, via e-mail, webchat and social media.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-11T10:45:16.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749547/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749547/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749547/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-06","Small Businesses: Coventry South","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to support micro-enterprises in Coventry South constituency.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","3438"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749548","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-11","<p>Science, Research and Innovation will be at the heart of our Industrial Strategy and this Government has bold ambitions to significantly increase research and development and back industries of the future. The Government’s vision is to achieve R&amp;D spending of 2.4% of GDP within ten years and 3% in the longer-term.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-07-11T14:30:13.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749548/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749548/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749548/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-06","Research: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, in what year the Government expects to reach a total spend of three per cent of gross domestic product on research and development.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","3481"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749549","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-11","<p>The government continues to believe that raising productivity is the best route to driving growth and raising long run living standards, as set out in “Fixing the foundations: Creating a more prosperous nation” - a plan for productivity growth in the UK. The government has since taken further steps, including the establishment of a National Productivity Investment Fund targeted at the productivity-critical areas of transport, R&amp;D, housing and digital communications. It is also making sure that young people have the skills that British businesses need through the reform of the technical education system and the introduction of T-levels.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-07-11T14:07:37.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749549/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749549/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749549/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-06","Productivity","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the Government has made any recent revisions to the UK's Productivity Plan.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","3479"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749550","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-14","<p>We are currently analysing the responses to the consultation and intend to publish an Industrial Strategy white paper in late 2017.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-07-14T08:28:21.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749550/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749550/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749550/answer","Devizes","Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749550/answer/previousversion/3663","Biography information for Claire Perry","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-06","Industry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when the Government plans to publish its response to the Building our Industrial Strategy consultation.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","3480"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749551","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-12","<p>The Chief Executive Officer of Ofgem wrote to my Rt Hon Friend the Secretary of State on the 3 July 2017 and the Chairman of the Gas and Electricity Markets Authority wrote to the Secretary of State on 6 July 2017.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-07-12T09:34:22.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749551/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749551/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749551/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-06","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what communication he has had with Ofgem, further to his letter dated 21 June 2017, on implementation of an energy price cap for households on standard variable tariffs.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","3451"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749552","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-14","<p>My rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State has had no such meetings. Higher Education policy is a matter for the Department for Education.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-07-14T10:44:57.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749552/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749552/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749552/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-06","Open University: Overseas Students","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent discussions he has had with the Open University on its use of a restricted countries list in its applications process.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","3498"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749553","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-26","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>My Rt Hon Friend the Secretary of State has written to Ofgem asking the regulator to advise him on the action it intends to take to safeguard customers on the poorest value tariffs.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-26T09:16:40.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749553/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749553/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749553/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-06","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment his Department has made of the merits of a relative price cap for domestic energy consumers.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","3449"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749554","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-12","<p>BEIS Ministers regularly meet with energy suppliers to discuss a range of issues.</p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-07-12T09:46:37.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749554/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749554/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749554/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-06","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent discussions he has had with energy suppliers on the implementation of an energy price cap for households on standard variable tariffs.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","3454"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749555","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-20","<p>In 2014-15, Central Government spent over £12 billion (27.1%) with small and medium sized businesses, which shows a continued year on year increase in SMEs winning public procurements. The Manifesto committed to ensuring of 33% of spend with SMEs by the end of this Parliament.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-07-20T13:06:14.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749555/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749555/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749555/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-06","Government Departments: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the Government is committed to awarding at least 33 per cent of government procurement to small and medium-sized enterprises by 2020.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","3444"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749556","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-12","<p>The Department has not undertaken to make any estimate for numbers of customers who would be protected, as no formal proposal has yet been made.</p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-07-12T09:58:32.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749556/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749556/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749556/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-06","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate his Department has made of the number of customers potentially covered by Ofgem's proposals for a price cap in the domestic energy market.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","3453"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749557","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-12","<p>Departments are currently conducting analysis with the Department for Exiting the EU to understand the impacts that withdrawal from the EU will have on businesses, consumers and other economic actors.</p><p>The renewable energy sector is a UK success story. Whatever happens in the future, the Government is committed to ensuring the UK remains a leader in this field.</p><p>We’re building a system fit for the 21st century, giving investors certainty and driving down the cost of renewable energy for our homes and businesses.</p><p>The second competitive Contracts for Difference allocation round is currently running, with a budget of £290m of annual support for 15 years for technologies including offshore wind.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-07-12T15:35:10.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749557/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749557/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749557/answer","Watford","Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749557/answer/previousversion/3656","Biography information for Richard Harrington","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-06","Renewable Energy: UK Trade with EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will assess the effect on the renewable energy sector of the UK leaving the EU without having agreed a trade deal with the EU.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","3497"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749558","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-14","<p>Departments are currently conducting analysis with the Department for Exiting the EU to understand the impacts that withdrawal will have on business, consumers and other economic actors. We are committed to securing the best possible deal with the EU and will ensure effective energy market operation and cross border trading of energy.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-07-14T08:47:25.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749558/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749558/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749558/answer","Watford","Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749558/answer/previousversion/3658","Biography information for Richard Harrington","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-06","Energy: UK Trade with EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will assess the effect on the energy sector of the UK leaving the EU without having agreed a trade deal with the EU.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","3496"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749559","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-11","<p>This Government has set out its vision to meet R&amp;D investment of 2.4% of GDP within ten years and 3% in the longer-term. Going forward, this ambition will be an important part of our Industrial Strategy and will require a concerted cross-government approach.</p><p> </p><p>We have already increased research and development investment by £4.7 billion over the period 2017-18 to 2020-21. This equates to an extra £2 billion per year by 2020-21 and is an increase of around 20% to total government R&amp;D spending, more than any increase in any parliament since 1979.</p><p> </p><p>The new Industrial Strategy Challenge Fund (ISCF), announced in November 2016, will back priority technologies where the UK has the potential to turn research strengths into a global industrial and commercial lead. The first wave of ISCF investment will be spent across six key challenges over the next 4 years and a variety of underpinning investments, driving progress in areas in which will support the industrial strategy. The ISCF is a UK wide fund for researchers and businesses across the UK.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-07-11T14:25:50.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749559/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749559/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749559/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-06","Research: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what his policy is on encouraging total public and private sector spending of three per cent of gross domestic product on research and development.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","3482"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749560","Department for International Trade","false","2017-07-12","<p>The Government has set out in the Queen's Speech its intentions to introduce the necessary trade legislation to develop an independent international trade policy upon exiting the European Union. Before such legislation is introduced, a supporting paper will be published.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-07-12T15:57:54.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749560/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749560/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749560/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-07-06","Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether he has plans to publish a White Paper on International Trade.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","3437"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749561","Department for International Trade","false","2017-07-14","<p>The Department for International Trade has a strong and capable trade policy team which has grown significantly since June 2016 (from 45 to over 300 today), and is continuing to grow.</p><p>We continue to hire the brightest and best talent from within the UK civil service and externally, in order to build a world class trade policy team that can deliver the best outcomes for the UK.</p><p>The Department has recently appointed Crawford Falconer to the role of Chief Trade Negotiation Adviser and Head of Trade Profession. Mr Falconer brings a wealth of global trade expertise from over 25 years of working on trade policy in the New Zealand government, the World Trade Organization and academia.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-07-14T13:57:32.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749561/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749561/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749561/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-07-06","Department for International Trade: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many staff of his Department work on trade negotiation.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","3516"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749562","Department for International Trade","false","2017-07-14","<p>The Department for International Trade (DIT) is working to deliver the best international trading framework for the UK to maximise global trade opportunities, including for the automotive sector. DIT Ministers and officials have frequent conversations with key stakeholders in the automotive sector, including through the Government’s partnership with the Automotive Council.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-07-14T11:30:18.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749562/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749562/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749562/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-07-06","Motor Vehicles: Manufacturing Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what recent discussions he has had with representatives of the automotive manufacturing industry.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","3513"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749563","Department for International Trade","false","2017-07-13","<p>I refer the hon. Member for Strangford to the answer I gave to my hon. Friend for Crawley on 6 July 2017, UIN: 2081.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-07-13T13:45:49.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749563/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749563/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749563/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-07-06","Overseas Trade: Commonwealth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what discussions he has had with Commonwealth trade ministers on (a) imports from Commonwealth countries to the UK and (b) exports from the UK to Commonwealth countries.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","3416"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749564","Department for International Trade","false","2017-07-14","<p>This department works closely with Invest Northern Ireland, promoting and showcasing Northern Ireland’s (NI) world-class cyber security capability, through our overseas network, inward missions and at major industry events such as Infosec and Mobile World Congress. More recently, this Department supported Invest Northern Ireland to secure investments from US cyber security companies: Black Duck Software and Rapid7, creating over 100 jobs in Northern Ireland. Northern Ireland is the number one international investment location for US cyber security firms. A US inward mission to showcase Northern Ireland’s technology and cyber security is scheduled for 2018.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-07-14T10:27:06.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749564/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749564/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749564/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-07-06","Cybercrime: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps he is taking to encourage inward investment in cyber security in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","3417"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749565","Department for International Trade","false","2017-07-14","<p>On December 7th, 2016, my Rt. Hon Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade met with Brazilian Finance Minister and UK investors based in Brazil on wider bi-lateral trade relationship. The meeting focussed on identifying a range of issues on which both sides shared a mutual interest.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-07-14T13:51:27.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749565/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749565/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749565/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-07-06","Overseas Trade: Brazil","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what discussions he has had with his counterpart in Brazil on the potential for trade in the agri-food sector.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","3418"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749566","Department for International Trade","false","2017-07-11","<p>There have been no staff who left or had agreed settlements to leave the Department for International Trade under (a) voluntary exit, (b) voluntary redundancy or (c) compulsory redundancy since 1 November 2016.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-07-11T13:53:36.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749566/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749566/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749566/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-07-06","Department for International Trade: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how many staff have left or agreed settlements to leave his Department under (a) voluntary exit, (b) voluntary redundancy and (c) compulsory redundancy since 1 November 2016; and how much compensation was paid in those cases.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","3366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749567","Department for International Trade","false","2017-07-13","<p>My Rt hon Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade visited Washington on 19-20 June and met with Commerce Secretary Wilbur Ross and US Trade Representative Robert Lighthizer. Their discussions covered a range of key UK interests including steel.</p><p>During the visit they agreed to convene a first meeting of the UK-US Trade Working Group in late July. Early discussions in the Working Group will focus on providing commercial continuity for US and UK businesses as the UK leaves the EU and on exploring possible ways to strengthen trade and commercial ties immediately, consistent with the EU’s common commercial policy. The Working Group will also work to lay the groundwork for a future UK-US free trade agreement once the UK has left the EU.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","3551 ; 3552 ; 3646","2017-07-13T14:41:14.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749567/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749567/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749567/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-07-06","Overseas Trade: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what recent discussions he has had with his counterpart in the US Administration on trade in meat products between the US and the UK.","false","Biography information for Hannah Bardell","Livingston","Hannah Bardell","3550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749568","Department for International Trade","false","2017-07-13","<p>My Rt hon Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade visited Washington on 19-20 June and met with Commerce Secretary Wilbur Ross and US Trade Representative Robert Lighthizer. Their discussions covered a range of key UK interests including steel.</p><p>During the visit they agreed to convene a first meeting of the UK-US Trade Working Group in late July. Early discussions in the Working Group will focus on providing commercial continuity for US and UK businesses as the UK leaves the EU and on exploring possible ways to strengthen trade and commercial ties immediately, consistent with the EU’s common commercial policy. The Working Group will also work to lay the groundwork for a future UK-US free trade agreement once the UK has left the EU.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","3550 ; 3552 ; 3646","2017-07-13T14:41:14.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749568/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749568/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749568/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-07-06","Overseas Trade: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what recent discussions he has had with his counterpart in the US Administration on trade in steel between the US and the UK.","false","Biography information for Hannah Bardell","Livingston","Hannah Bardell","3551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749569","Department for International Trade","false","2017-07-13","<p>My Rt hon Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade visited Washington on 19-20 June and met with Commerce Secretary Wilbur Ross and US Trade Representative Robert Lighthizer. Their discussions covered a range of key UK interests including steel.</p><p>During the visit they agreed to convene a first meeting of the UK-US Trade Working Group in late July. Early discussions in the Working Group will focus on providing commercial continuity for US and UK businesses as the UK leaves the EU and on exploring possible ways to strengthen trade and commercial ties immediately, consistent with the EU’s common commercial policy. The Working Group will also work to lay the groundwork for a future UK-US free trade agreement once the UK has left the EU.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","3550 ; 3551 ; 3646","2017-07-13T14:41:15.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749569/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749569/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749569/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-07-06","Overseas Trade: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, when he last met his counterpart in the US Administration; and what matters were discussed.","false","Biography information for Hannah Bardell","Livingston","Hannah Bardell","3552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749570","Department for International Trade","false","2017-07-11","<p>The Department for International Trade (DIT) promotes trade and investment across the world and champions global free trade.</p><p>This department's support is targeted where government can add most value. We prioritise our global export promotion activity by identifying the sector-market combinations that present the greatest opportunities to achieve the maximum impact and success. The Department currently has 23 High Value Campaigns across the energy sector including oil &amp; gas, civil nuclear and renewables.</p><p>UK Export Finance (UKEF) actively works with project sponsors to bring business to the UK. In the past 5 years, UKEF has provided over £2bn in support of energy exports.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-07-11T13:55:05.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749570/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749570/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749570/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-07-06","Energy: Exports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps his Department is taking to encourage businesses in the energy sector to take advantage of new export opportunities and international trade.","false","Biography information for Ross Thomson","Aberdeen South","Ross Thomson","3576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749571","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-17","There is no need to do anything now. The UK will remain a member of the EU until March 2019 and there will be no change to the rights and status of EU citizens living in the UK, nor UK nationals living in the EU, during this time. Permanent residence status is linked to the UK’s membership of the EU and so will no longer be valid after we leave. Therefore EU citizens do not need to apply for documentation confirming their permanent residence status. We will be asking EU citizens to make an application to the Home Office for documentation demonstrating their new settled status in due course. We will make the process as streamlined as possible for all individuals, including those who already hold a residence document under current free movement rules. <strong>Our intention is that the grace period last up to two years, giving people plenty of time to regularise their status.</strong> Anyone who would like to find out the latest information, including when they will need to sign up for the new scheme, can sign-up for email updates here.","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-07-17T07:52:21.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749571/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749571/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749571/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-06","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to paragraph 10 of his Department's policy paper entitled Safeguarding the position of EU citizens in the UK and UK nationals in the EU, published on 26 June 2017, what additional steps people who have received permanent residence documentation will have to take in order to secure settled status.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","3553"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749572","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-14","<p>Our offer applies to all EU citizens equally. We will not treat citizens of one member state differently to those of another, except regarding the special arrangements for Irish nationals. Our offer clearly sets out that EU citizens who have settled status will be treated the same as comparable UK nationals.</p><p>We have set out a fair offer to protect the rights and entitlements of EU nationals living in the UK. Settled status will be offered to those that have been continuously resident in the UK for 5 years. Those that have been here for less will be eligible for temporary leave which allows them to remain in the UK with the same broad set of rights and entitlements as they do now until they can get settled status.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-07-14T10:26:50.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749572/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749572/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749572/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-06","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to paragraph 6 of his Department's policy paper entitled Safeguarding the position of EU citizens in the UK and UK nationals in the EU, published on 26 June 2017, whether non-UK EU nationals will continue to benefit from the right to equal treatment in the UK after the specified date.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","3554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749573","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-12","<p>Any EU citizen in the UK before the specified date with five years’ continuous residence will be able to apply for UK settled status. Other EU citizens who arrive before the specified date will be able to stay until they have the five years’ residence to apply for UK settled status.</p><p>Five years’ continuous residence is the period in EU law required, in most cases, for acquiring permanent residence status, and also under UK law for non-EEA nationals acquiring indefinite leave to remain.</p><p>It is considered across the immigration system to be the period of time when an individual is fully integrated, and has contributed enough to the UK economy and society for restrictions on their immigration status to be lifted and for them to be able to settle here permanently.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-07-12T12:13:03.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749573/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749573/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749573/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-06","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how continuous residence in paragraph 6 of his Department's policy paper entitled Safeguarding the position of EU citizens in the UK and UK nationals in the EU, published on 26 June 2017, is defined.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","3555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749574","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-14","<p>Those EU citizens who arrived and became a resident before the specified date but who have not accrued five years’ continuous residence at the time of the UK’s exit will be able to apply for temporary status in order to remain resident in the UK until they have accumulated five years, after which they will be eligible to apply for settled status.</p><p>EU citizens on this pathway to settled status will continue to be able to access the same benefits that they can access now. If these individuals go on to acquire settled status, they will then be able to access benefits on the same terms as comparable UK residents.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-07-14T10:25:22.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749574/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749574/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749574/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-06","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to paragraph 6 of his Department's policy paper entitled Safeguarding the position of EU citizens in the UK and UK nationals in the EU, published on 26 June 2017, what rights and entitlements a non-UK EU citizen will have who arrived in the UK before the specified date but has not lived in the UK for five years.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","3556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749575","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-14","<p>Family members of eligible EU citizens resident in the UK before we leave the EU will be able to apply for settled status after five years, whether they are EU or non-EU citizens. They will be subject to the same rules that apply to non-EU nationals joining British citizens, or alternatively to the post-exit immigration arrangements for EU citizens who arrive after the specified date.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-07-14T11:05:52.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749575/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749575/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749575/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-06","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to paragraph 6 of his Department's policy paper entitled, Safeguarding the position of EU citizens in the UK and UK nationals in the EU, published on 26 June 2017, whether family dependents of non-UK EU citizens in the UK who arrive after the specified date will be subject to the immigration rules in respect of their family members.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","3557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749576","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-13","<p>The Government intends to make the process as streamlined as possible for all individuals. We intend to use existing government data, such as income records, to minimise the burden of documentary evidence required (for example, to prove continuous residence). It is likely that those EU citizens and their family members who wish to take advantage of the streamlined digital process will need to provide evidence of their passport to prove their identity.</p><p>More details on the new scheme will be provided once agreement is reached with the EU. We intend to make the new application process as user friendly as possible.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-07-13T15:39:11.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749576/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749576/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749576/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-06","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to paragraph 35 of his Department's policy paper entitled, Safeguarding the position of EU citizens in the UK and UK nationals in the EU, published on 26 June 2017, what evidence non-UK EU nationals will need to provide in order to prove five years' residence and obtain settled status.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","3558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749577","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-12","<p>The two essential conditions an EU national must meet in order to obtain settled status are firstly, that they have been resident in the UK for 5 years and secondly, that they are not considered to be a threat to the UK, through an assessment of conduct and criminality.</p><p>The application process will be as streamlined and user-friendly as possible. Further details will be published in due course.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-07-12T10:56:20.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749577/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749577/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749577/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-06","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to paragraph 37 of his Department's policy paper entitled, Safeguarding the position of EU citizens in the UK and UK nationals in the EU, published on 26 June 2017, whether the criteria for obtaining settled status will differ from that for obtaining permanent residence currently; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","3559"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749578","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-13","<p>Those who have been living in the UK for five years before the specified date and want to continue to make the UK their home will be able to apply for settled status to stay indefinitely after we exit.</p><p>As is the case for those holding permanent residence status under EU law, those who have already lived in the UK for over five years but were not present at the time of the specified date will still be eligible for settled status if that absence was less than two consecutive years.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-07-13T15:42:30.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749578/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749578/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749578/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-06","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to his Department's policy paper entitled, Safeguarding the position of EU citizens in the UK and UK nationals in the EU, published on 26 June 2017, what plans he has in respect of the (a) residence and (b) acquired EU rights of non-UK EU nationals who have previously lived in the UK but are no longer resident in the UK.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","3560"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749579","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-14","<p>For those who have been living in the UK for five years and want to continue to make the UK their home, they will be able to apply for settled status to stay indefinitely after we exit.</p><p>As is the case for those holding permanent residence status under EU law, for those who have already lived in the UK for over five years but were not present at the time of the specified date, they will still be eligible for settled status if that absence was for less than two consecutive years.</p><p>We have also been clear that we want to secure a reciprocal agreement for UK nationals in the EU which could apply in the same way.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-07-14T10:22:25.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749579/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749579/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749579/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-06","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to his Department's policy paper entitled, Safeguarding the position of EU citizens in the UK and UK nationals in the EU, published on 26 June 2017, what his proposals mean for the (a) residence and (b) acquired EU rights of UK nationals who have previously lived in another EU Member State but are no longer resident in that country.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","3561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749580","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-12","<p>We are planning to set up an application process before we leave the EU to enable those who wish to do so to get their new settled status at their earliest convenience. For those who have already obtained a certificate of their permanent residence, we will seek to make sure that the application process for settled status is as streamlined as possible.<br><br>The UK Government and the Commission have stated that providing certainty to citizens is a priority. This is why we want to reach a reciprocal agreement for EU citizens in UK and UK nationals in the EU as quickly as possible. It is already clear that there is much common ground between the UK and EU positions and we are confident that we can reach an agreement on this important issue early in negotiations.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-07-12T12:14:14.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749580/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749580/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749580/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-06","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whether the Government plans to implement any of the proposals in his Department's policy paper entitled, Safeguarding the position of EU citizens in the UK and UK nationals in the EU, published on 26 June 2017 before the conclusion of the negotiations on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","3562"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749581","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-17","<p>The Government fully recognises that those EU citizens resident in the UK before the specific date, and UK national resident in EU Member States, enjoy access to public services such as healthcare a, education, employment and housing. We are proposing a reciprocal deal that will protect the right of UK national in the EU to continue to live and work in the EU.</p>This includes the ability to work in one Member State but live in another, for those to whom this applies.","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-07-17T07:53:20.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749581/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749581/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749581/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-06","Immigration: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to paragraph 45 of his Department's policy paper entitled, Safeguarding the position of EU citizens in the UK and UK nationals in the EU, published on 26 June 2017, what his policy is on preserving the right of UK nationals to move and reside in other EU Member States after the UK ceases to be a member of the EU as part of the negotiations on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","3563"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749582","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-14","<p>Until the UK’s exit, EU citizens resident here will continue to enjoy the rights they have under EU Treaties. After we leave the EU, we will create new rights in UK law for qualifying EU citizens which will be enforceable in the UK legal system. EU citizens that acquire settled status will have access to UK benefits, pensions, healthcare and other rights on the same basis as a comparable UK national.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-07-14T10:24:03.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749582/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749582/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749582/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-06","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, which rights accruing from EU citizenship non-UK EU nationals will lose as a result of transitioning to the settled status outlined in his Department's policy document entitled, Safeguarding the position of EU citizens in the UK and UK nationals in the EU, published on 26 June 2017.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","3564"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749583","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-14","<p>Details of the number, type, compensation levels and cost of exits from The Department for Exiting the European Union will be routinely published in the Department’s Annual Report and Accounts.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-07-14T11:09:06.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749583/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749583/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749583/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-06","Department for Exiting the European Union: Redundancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many staff have left or agreed settlements to leave his Department under (a) voluntary exit, (b) voluntary redundancy and (c) compulsory redundancy since 1 November 2016; and how much compensation was paid in those cases.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","3362"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749584","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-14","<p>The Government has frequent conversations with key stakeholders in the automotive sector, including through our partnership with the Automotive Council. Since the Department was created, we have pursued a wide-ranging programme of engagement in order to build a national consensus around our negotiating position.</p><p>This engagement has included a roundtable held in December 2016 with key automotive businesses held by the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, joined by Ministers from the Department for Transport and the Department for Business, Energy &amp; Industrial Strategy. This dialogue will continue as negotiations progress.</p><p>Details of Ministerial and senior official meetings will be published in the Department’s Quarterly Transparency Returns, which will be made publicly available on GOV.UK.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-07-14T13:07:47.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749584/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749584/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749584/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-06","Motor Vehicles: Manufacturing Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what recent discussions he has had with representatives of the automotive manufacturing industry.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","3514"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749585","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-11","<p>EU citizens who already have 5 years’ continuous residence in the UK will be immediately eligible for settled status. Those who arrived before the specified date but do not yet meet the 5 year threshold by exit day will be allowed to stay until they reach that milestone and can also secure settled status. These rules will apply regardless of citizens’ income levels.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-07-11T14:14:47.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749585/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749585/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749585/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-06","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to paragraph 6 of his Department's policy paper entitled Safeguarding the position of EU citizens in the UK and UK nationals in the EU, published on 26 June 2017, whether there will be a minimum income threshold to obtain settled status.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","3595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749586","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-11","<p>Fees and charges are being considered as part of the negotiations. Our aim is to offer a streamlined and high quality service for everyone, keeping fees at a reasonable level. We will make the process as streamlined as possible for all individuals, including those who already hold a residence document under current free movement rules. As set out in the paper, we will publish further details in due course.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-07-11T14:19:09.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749586/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749586/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749586/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-06","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to paragraph 36 of his Department's policy paper entitled Safeguarding the position of EU citizens in the UK and UK nationals in the EU, published on 26 June 2017, whether the fee to apply for settled status will exceed the current fee to make an application for a permanent residence document.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","3596"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749587","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-11","<p>The policy proposals contained in the paper outline our fair and serious offer to citizens. Following negotiations, agreements will be enshrined in UK law and enforceable through the UK judicial system, up to and including the Supreme Court. We are also ready to make commitments in the Withdrawal Agreement which will have the status of international law.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-07-11T14:16:21.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749587/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749587/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749587/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-06","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to his Department's policy paper entitled Safeguarding the position of EU citizens in the UK and UK nationals in the EU, published on 26 June 2017, what legal status he plans to accord the policy proposals contained in that paper; and what plans he has to ensure the enforceability of those rights.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","3597"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749588","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-14","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union has not incurred any spend on advertising on social media in any month since January 2016.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-07-14T11:07:49.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749588/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749588/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/749588/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-06","Department for Exiting the European Union: Advertising","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how much his Department has spent on advertising on social media in each month since January 2016.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","3407"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750623","Department for International Development","false","2017-07-12","<p>The UK ended its traditional bilateral aid programmes with China in 2011 and ended all financial aid to the Indian government in 2015. Instead the UK is now building relationships with these countries focused on trade and investment and on working together on global issues. We need to be clear that the Prosperity Fund is part of this new more mature partnership and allows us to share cutting edge UK expertise to support economic growth and development. This is good for these countries but is also strongly in our own national interest.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-07-12T14:06:46.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750623/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750623/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750623/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-07-06","Prosperity Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of the Prosperity Fund in the delivery of her Department's goals.","false","Biography information for Richard Graham","Gloucester","Richard Graham","900372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750624","Department for International Development","false","2017-07-12","<p>Trade brings economic growth to developing countries and benefits UK producers and consumers. That is why on 25 June I announced that as we leave the EU, we will secure duty-free access to UK markets for the Least Developed Countries. Once we have left, we will build on our track-record as a champion of trade and development, strengthening our existing support and seizing new opportunities to increase trade links.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2017-07-12T14:08:20.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750624/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750624/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750624/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-07-06","Developing Countries: Overseas Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps the Government is taking to promote trade between the UK and the Least Developed Countries.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","900373"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750625","Department for International Development","false","2017-07-12","<p>Developing connections between schools in the UK and in poorer countries can bring benefits to all the children involved. Through our Connecting Classrooms programme we are giving British children the chance to act as Global Britain's ambassadors, to build international partnerships and to shape the world they want to live in.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-07-12T13:59:56.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750625/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750625/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750625/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-07-06","Africa: Schools","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what her policy is on the development of relations between schools in the UK and in Africa.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","900370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750626","Department for International Development","false","2017-07-12","<p>According to the UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs, most homes in Gaza are only getting water for a few hours every 3-5 days. The availability of safe drinking water has become worse because of fuel and electricity shortages. The UK is urging all parties to find a sustainable solution to the current situation and in the longer term, continues to urge the Israeli authorities to ensure fair distribution of water across the OPTs.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-07-12T15:53:12.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750626/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750626/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/750626/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-07-06","Gaza: Drinking Water","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what recent assessment she has made of the availability of safe drinking water in the Gaza Strip.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","900371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748440","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-12","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","3288 ; 3289 ; 3290","2017-07-12T11:01:46.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748440/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748440/answer","PQ3287_ 3288_ 3289_ 3290 holding response.pdf","UKSA Response to PQ3287, 3288, 3289, 3290","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748440/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-05","Offshore Industry: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many (a) employees and (b) self-employed workers were classified as working on oil and gas installations on the UK Continental Shelf in each year between 2008-09 and 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","3287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748441","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-12","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","3287 ; 3289 ; 3290","2017-07-12T11:01:46.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748441/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748441/answer","PQ3287_ 3288_ 3289_ 3290 holding response.pdf","UKSA Response to PQ3287, 3288, 3289, 3290","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/748441/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-05","Offshore Industry: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many (a) employees and (b) self-employed workers were classified as working on offshore wind projects on the UK Continental Shelf in each year between 2008-09 and 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Alex Cunningham","Stockton North","Alex Cunningham","3288"
